{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538564"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16221"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16221"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.08,0.06,0.04,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8912"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"4106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4107"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21206"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of progressive left vulval pain and swelling. She reports similar episodes over the past eight months that resolved spontaneously. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with a regular partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a tender, fluctuant 3 cm mass at the left posterior introitus at the 8 o\u0027clock position. The overlying skin is erythematous but intact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Marsupialisation","Conservative management","Simple excision","Broad-spectrum antibiotics","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a symptomatic Bartholin\u0027s cyst with features suggesting superimposed infection (abscess). The history of recurrence suggests the need for definitive management rather than temporary measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarsupialisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate definitive treatment for symptomatic or recurrent Bartholin\u0027s cysts. The procedure involves creating a permanent opening by suturing the cyst wall to the surrounding tissue, preventing re-accumulation of fluid. It can be performed under local anaesthesia and has a success rate of approximately 85%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E with sitz baths and analgesia may be appropriate for first presentations or asymptomatic cysts, but given this patient\u0027s history of recurrence, definitive treatment is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple excision\u003C/strong\u003E of the Bartholin\u0027s gland carries a higher risk of complications including bleeding, scarring, and dyspareunia compared to marsupialisation, and is generally reserved for cases where malignancy is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad-spectrum antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated as an adjunct treatment if there is evidence of infection, but they do not address the underlying anatomical problem and will not prevent recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while providing immediate relief, has a high recurrence rate (up to 20%) because the cyst wall remains intact. It is appropriate only for emergency temporary relief of an abscess if definitive treatment must be delayed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bartholin\u0027s cyst marsupialisation is the definitive treatment for symptomatic or recurrent Bartholin\u0027s cysts.","Incision and drainage alone has a high recurrence rate and should be avoided as definitive management."],"references":["Omole F, Simmons BJ, Hacker Y. Management of Bartholin\u0027s duct cyst and gland abscess. Am Fam Physician. 2003;68(1):135-140. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2003/0701/p135.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16221"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T14:39:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T14:41:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8912"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64391"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","lin